      "source": [
        "# PTS Regression Analysis\n",
        "Scoring is arguably the single most important factor impacting the outcome of basketball games. Due to this, we aim to predict a player's total points (pts), which is a challenge that can be effectively addressed using regression analysis. Through analyzing the relationship between performance metrics and points scored, regression models allow us to quantify the contributions of each variable to players' scoring output while predicting future scoring performances with varying accuracy levels."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": 6,
      "metadata": {
        "colab": {
          "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/"
        },
        "id": "9B4t6tg6QG4Z",
        "outputId": "b747661c-8a54-4c9d-e6b9-9b1a508d33aa"
      },
      "outputs": [
        {
          "name": "stdout",
          "output_type": "stream",
          "text": [
            "X_train shape: (588, 45)\n",
            "X_test shape: (148, 45)\n",
            "y_train shape: (588,)\n",
            "y_test shape: (148,)\n"
          ]
        }
      ],
      "source": [
        "#remove our y variable (pts)\n",
        "numerical_cols.remove('PTS')\n",
        "\n",
        "#create train and test sets to fit and test the following models\n",
        "X = player_stats[numerical_cols]\n",
        "y = player_stats['PTS']\n",
        "\n",
        "# Split the data into training and testing sets using 80/20% slpit\n",
        "X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.2, random_state=11)\n",
        "\n",
        "print(f\"X_train shape: {X_train.shape}\")\n",
        "print(f\"X_test shape: {X_test.shape}\")\n",
        "print(f\"y_train shape: {y_train.shape}\")\n",
        "print(f\"y_test shape: {y_test.shape}\")"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "oh6jh-HBSWRq"
      },
      "source": [
        "First, let's start by fitting a linear regression model using all variables as predictors."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": 7,
      "metadata": {
        "colab": {
          "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/"
        },
        "id": "XcqMZ2J9QG7M",
        "outputId": "fcd5fa58-e990-4568-bdc0-6a187d7b622b"
      },
      "outputs": [
        {
          "name": "stdout",
          "output_type": "stream",
          "text": [
            "Mean Squared Error (MSE): 0.01\n",
            "R-squared (R2): 1.00\n"
          ]
        }
      ],
      "source": [
        "# Initialize and train the Linear Regression model on train data\n",
        "model = LinearRegression()\n",
        "model.fit(X_train, y_train)\n",
        "\n",
        "# Make predictions on the test set\n",
        "y_pred = model.predict(X_test)\n",
        "\n",
        "# Evaluate the model\n",
        "mse = mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred)\n",
        "r2 = r2_score(y_test, y_pred)\n",
        "\n",
        "print(f\"Mean Squared Error (MSE): {mse:.2f}\")\n",
        "print(f\"R-squared (R2): {r2:.2f}\")"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "RlwDTx2STWHt"
      },
      "source": [
        "Our results are very impressive as R^2 = 1 suggests that our model explains 100% of the variability in the true observations (pts), while a MSE = 0.01 means our predicted pts values are nearly identical to the actual pts values on average. However, including scoring variables such as FG, FGA, and others may help the model too much to the point where the model is just making calculations rather than predictions. To fix this, let's try again without these direct scoring variables to ensure our model is making predictions."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": 19,
      "metadata": {
        "colab": {
          "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/"
        },
        "id": "8h_zjuWBQG92",
        "outputId": "2281092c-4057-4785-dd0e-a4eb40ca8f54"
      },
      "outputs": [
        {
          "name": "stdout",
          "output_type": "stream",
          "text": [
            "X_train shape: (588, 32)\n",
            "X_test shape: (148, 32)\n",
            "y_train shape: (588,)\n",
            "y_test shape: (148,)\n"
          ]
        }
      ],
      "source": [
        "#remove variables directly tied to scoring\n",
        "scoring_features = [\"FG\", \"FGA\", \"FG%\", \"3P\", \"3PA\", \"3P%\", \"2P\", \"2PA\", \"2P%\", \"eFG%\", \"FT\", \"FTA\", \"FT%\"]\n",
        "nonscoring_numeric = [col for col in numerical_cols if col not in scoring_features]\n",
        "\n",
        "#create new x and y variables\n",
        "\n",
        "X = player_stats[nonscoring_numeric]\n",
        "y = player_stats['PTS']\n",
        "\n",
        "#split into train and test\n",
        "X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.2, random_state=11)\n",
        "\n",
        "print(f\"X_train shape: {X_train.shape}\")\n",
        "print(f\"X_test shape: {X_test.shape}\")\n",
        "print(f\"y_train shape: {y_train.shape}\")\n",
        "print(f\"y_test shape: {y_test.shape}\")\n",
        "\n"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": 22,
      "metadata": {
        "colab": {
          "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/"
        },
        "id": "cn9mmwMdWb1a",
        "outputId": "b304b431-865e-40c1-a19a-f1764779cf27"
      },
      "outputs": [
        {
          "name": "stdout",
          "output_type": "stream",
          "text": [
            "Mean Squared Error (MSE): 1.17\n",
            "R-squared (R2): 0.97\n"
          ]
        }
      ],
      "source": [
        "#fit linear regression model\n",
        "# Initialize and train the Linear Regression model on train data\n",
        "model = LinearRegression()\n",
        "model.fit(X_train, y_train)\n",
        "\n",
        "# Make predictions on the test set\n",
        "y_pred = model.predict(X_test)\n",
        "\n",
        "# Evaluate the model\n",
        "mse = mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred)\n",
        "r2 = r2_score(y_test, y_pred)\n",
        "\n",
        "print(f\"Mean Squared Error (MSE): {mse:.2f}\")\n",
        "print(f\"R-squared (R2): {r2:.2f}\")\n"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "cdXZ_4i3XnRF"
      },
      "source": [
        "Now we have a model that still performs very well, explaining 97% of the variation in PTS, with a MSE of 1.17, suggesting accurate predictions on average. But our model is not very interpretable with 32 coefficients, as you can see below."
      ]
    },
    {
