      ],
      "source": [
        "print(\"number of model coefficients\")\n",
        "print(len(model.coef_))\n",
        "\n",
        "print(\"Coefficient Values:\")\n",
        "for feature, coef_val in zip(nonscoring_numeric, model.coef_):\n",
        "    print(f\"{feature}: {coef_val:.4f}\")"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "aGNBlqOTYbBc"
      },
      "source": [
        "From this, we still don't know the most important variables, and their impact on predicted values. To solve this, we will use lasso regression to put a penalty on coefficient values in order to shrink them, and potentially perform variable selection in the process. We will first use k = 10 cross-validation to find the optimal lambda value for our model.  "
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": 32,
      "metadata": {
        "colab": {
          "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/"
        },
        "id": "ptjL2w-WY6_c",
        "outputId": "ec79f95a-8a9d-4b7a-85e3-06d1e104997d"
      },
      "outputs": [
        {
          "name": "stdout",
          "output_type": "stream",
          "text": [
            "Optimal lambda value: 0.1119\n",
            "Mean Squared Error (MSE): 2.00\n",
            "R-squared (R2): 0.95\n",
            "Age: 0.0000\n",
            "G: -0.0127\n",
            "GS: 0.0088\n",
            "MP: 0.4024\n",
            "ORB: -0.0000\n",
            "DRB: 0.0000\n",
            "TRB: -0.0000\n",
            "AST: -0.0000\n",
            "STL: -0.0000\n",
            "BLK: -0.0000\n",
            "TOV: 0.5442\n",
            "PF: -0.0000\n",
            "PER: 0.1464\n",
            "TS%: 0.0000\n",
            "3PAr: -0.0000\n",
            "FTr: 0.0000\n",
            "ORB%: -0.0986\n",
            "DRB%: -0.0249\n",
            "TRB%: -0.0000\n",
            "AST%: -0.0331\n",
            "STL%: -0.1145\n",
            "BLK%: -0.0000\n",
            "TOV%: -0.0011\n",
            "USG%: 0.3260\n",
            "OWS: 0.1710\n",
            "DWS: -0.0277\n",
            "WS: 0.0000\n",
            "WS/48: 0.0000\n",
            "OBPM: 0.0209\n",
            "DBPM: -0.0000\n",
            "BPM: 0.0000\n",
            "VORP: 0.7227\n"
          ]
        }
      ],
      "source": [
        "#create lasso model with k = 10 CV.\n",
        "lasso_cv_model = LassoCV(cv=10, max_iter=100000, random_state = 11)\n",
        "\n",
        "#fit model\n",
        "lasso_cv_model.fit(X_train, y_train)\n",
        "\n",
        "#get optimal lambda value found from CV\n",
        "optimal_lambda = lasso_cv_model.alpha_\n",
        "print(f\"Optimal lambda value: {optimal_lambda:.4f}\")\n",
        "\n",
        "#now make predictions on test set\n",
        "y_pred = lasso_cv_model.predict(X_test)\n",
        "\n",
        "#evaluate model\n",
        "mse = mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred)\n",
        "R2 = r2_score(y_test, y_pred)\n",
        "\n",
        "print(f\"Mean Squared Error (MSE): {mse:.2f}\")\n",
        "print(f\"R-squared (R2): {R2:.2f}\")\n",
        "\n",
        "for var, coef in zip(nonscoring_numeric, lasso_cv_model.coef_):\n",
        "  print(f\"{var}: {coef:.4f}\")\n"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "cGyTwQEYfpGS"
      },
      "source": [
        "We see with the lasso model, it still works very well, explaining 95% of variability in PTS, with a MSE = 2, suggesting accurate predictions on average. We also see that many variable coefficients have been reduced to 0. This is one of the benefits of Lasso regression, as it is able to perform variable selection. As a result, we have a model that performs slightly worse, but is much more interpretable, which is a good trade-off in this case."
      ]
    },
