      "source": [
        "# Plotting the important coefficients for PER prediction\n",
        "plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))\n",
        "sns.barplot(x='Coefficient', y='variable', data=important_features, palette='viridis')\n",
        "plt.title('Important Coefficients from LassoCV Model for PER (Non-zero)')\n",
        "plt.xlabel('Coefficient Value')\n",
        "plt.ylabel('Variable')\n",
        "plt.grid(axis='x', linestyle='--', alpha=0.7)\n",
        "plt.tight_layout()\n",
        "plt.show()"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "yR1JiU7Qnz9H"
      },
      "source": [
        "We see that eFG%, a player's field goal percentage with weight added for the benefit of a 3-point shot over a 2-point shot, is the most important basic stat in predicting a player's PER. This shows how significantly a player's shooting efficiency contributes to what PER determines as positive contributions for a player on the court, and the role that efficient scoring contributes to a player's perceived impact on winning. We see that TOV is the biggest negative coefficient value, likely indicating that turnovers contribute the most to negative impact when calculating PER, while MP (minutes played) also negatively contributes to a player's PER, indicating that minutes played without positive impacting factors contributed will decrease a player's PER."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "KmxIWbs5pebw"
      },
      "source": [
        "Next, we will introduce non-linear terms to allow us to fit more complex non-linear relationships between the variables. By applying this to our PER prediction modelling process, we can see of oy improves model performance by capturing non-linear patterns."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": 51,
      "metadata": {
        "colab": {
          "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/"
        },
        "id": "SEspOHMepeqp",
        "outputId": "d29a90e8-9293-467b-d66e-4dbeaaa9a088"
      },
      "outputs": [
        {
          "name": "stdout",
          "output_type": "stream",
          "text": [
            "New number of features 350\n",
            "Mean Squared Error (MSE): 7.85\n",
            "R-squared (R2): 0.79\n"
          ]
        }
      ],
      "source": [
        "#create polynomial features\n",
        "poly = PolynomialFeatures(degree=2, include_bias=False)\n",
        "X_basic_poly = poly.fit_transform(X_basic_stats)\n",
        "\n",
        "X_train_per, X_test_per, y_train_per, y_test_per = train_test_split(X_basic_poly, y_per, test_size=0.2, random_state=11)\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "print(\"New number of features\", X_basic_poly.shape[1])\n",
        "#create and fit model\n",
        "per_model_poly = LinearRegression()\n",
        "per_model_poly.fit(X_train_per, y_train_per)\n",
        "#make predictions\n",
        "y_pred = per_model_poly.predict(X_test_per)\n",
        "#evaluate model\n",
        "mse = mean_squared_error(y_test_per, y_pred)\n",
        "R2 = r2_score(y_test_per, y_pred)\n",
        "\n",
        "print(f\"Mean Squared Error (MSE): {mse:.2f}\")\n",
        "print(f\"R-squared (R2): {R2:.2f}\")\n",
        "\n"
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "VrHhtOdzrTiJ"
      },
      "source": [
        "We see an improvement in the model as it now explain 79% of the variation in the PER, with a lower MSE = 7.85. However, due to the increase in dimensionality with now 350 predictor variables, we increase the risk of overfitting the data."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {
        "id": "baa325f0"
      },
      "source": [
        "### Selected Polynomial Terms for PER Prediction\n",
        "\n",
        "We will now incorporate polynomial terms for `eFG%`, `TOV`, and `MP` into our feature set. These variables were chosen due to their significant impact on PER in previous models and the plausible existence of non-linear relationships with player efficiency, while not wanting to include too many new interactions as we did above. We will use `PolynomialFeatures` to generate degree-2 polynomial terms and then combine them with the original `X_basic_stats` before training a new linear regression model."
      ]
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "execution_count": 56,
      "metadata": {
        "colab": {
          "base_uri": "https://localhost:8080/"
        },
        "id": "1ac1d1e8",
        "outputId": "349a61d3-c4f3-4494-9980-d203a76a1fcf"
      },
      "outputs": [
        {
          "name": "stdout",
          "output_type": "stream",
          "text": [
            "Original number of features: 25\n",
            "Number of features after adding selected polynomial terms: 34\n",
            "Mean Squared Error (MSE) with Selected Polynomial Features: 8.59\n",
            "R-squared (R2) with Selected Polynomial Features: 0.77\n"
          ]
        }
      ],
      "source": [
        "# Select important variables\n",
        "selected_poly_features = ['eFG%', 'TOV', 'MP']\n",
        "\n",
        "# Create polynomial features for these selected variables (degree 2)\n",
        "poly_selected = PolynomialFeatures(degree=2, include_bias=False)\n",
        "X_selected_poly = poly_selected.fit_transform(X_basic_stats[selected_poly_features])\n",
        "\n",
        "# Get the names of the new polynomial features\n",
        "poly_feature_names = poly_selected.get_feature_names_out(selected_poly_features)\n",
        "\n",
        "# Create a DataFrame from the new polynomial features, preserving the original index\n",
        "X_selected_poly_df = pd.DataFrame(X_selected_poly, columns=poly_feature_names, index=X_basic_stats.index)\n",
        "\n",
        "# Combine original X_basic_stats with the new selected polynomial features.\n",
        "# We concatenate to keep both the original and polynomial terms for the selected features.\n",
        "X_per_combined_poly = pd.concat([X_basic_stats, X_selected_poly_df], axis=1)\n",
        "\n",
        "print(f\"Original number of features: {X_basic_stats.shape[1]}\")\n",
        "print(f\"Number of features after adding selected polynomial terms: {X_per_combined_poly.shape[1]}\")\n",
        "\n",
        "# Split the combined data into training and testing sets\n",
        "X_train_per_combined_poly, X_test_per_combined_poly, y_train_per, y_test_per = train_test_split(\n",
        "    X_per_combined_poly, y_per, test_size=0.2, random_state=11\n",
        ")\n",
        "\n",
        "# Initialize and train a Linear Regression model on the combined features\n",
        "per_model_combined_poly = LinearRegression()\n",
        "per_model_combined_poly.fit(X_train_per_combined_poly, y_train_per)\n",
        "\n",
        "# Make predictions on the test set\n",
        "y_pred_per_combined_poly = per_model_combined_poly.predict(X_test_per_combined_poly)\n",
        "\n",
        "# Evaluate the model\n",
        "mse_combined_poly = mean_squared_error(y_test_per, y_pred_per_combined_poly)\n",
        "r2_combined_poly = r2_score(y_test_per, y_pred_per_combined_poly)\n",
        "\n",
        "print(f\"Mean Squared Error (MSE) with Selected Polynomial Features: {mse_combined_poly:.2f}\")\n",
        "print(f\"R-squared (R2) with Selected Polynomial Features: {r2_combined_poly:.2f}\")"
      ]
